def cat_num (df):
    for typ,col in zip(df.dtypes.values,df.dtypes.index):
        if typ == "object":
             cat_col.append(col)
        else:
            num_col.append(col);

def cat_count(df):
    cat_columns = df[cat_col]
    for col in cat_columns:
        print(f'value counts dari column {col}')
        print(df[col].value_counts())
        print('---'*10, '\n');

  • The vicious cycle, including poverty, hunger, and inequalities tends to have a positive correlation with each other
  • The rise of diesel fuel is negatively correlated with the vicious cycle and positively correlated with the rise of some renewable energy consumption.

def standard(x):
    import pandas as pd
    from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    y = scaler.fit_transform(x)
    z = pd.DataFrame(y).fillna(0)
    return z

df_standar = standard(df_cluster)

Find Number of Optimal Cluster using Elbow Method

In [34]:
inertia = []

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
for i in range(2, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(df_standar)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)



plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

sns.lineplot(x=range(2, 11), y=inertia, color='#000087', linewidth = 4)
sns.scatterplot(x=range(2, 11), y=inertia, s=300, color='#800000',  linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Find Number of Optimal Cluster using Silhoutte

In [35]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
range_n_clusters = list(range(2,11))
arr_silhouette_score_euclidean = []
for i in range_n_clusters:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i).fit(df_standar)
    preds = kmeans.predict(df_standar)
     
    score_euclidean = silhouette_score(df_standar, preds, metric='euclidean')
    arr_silhouette_score_euclidean.append(score_euclidean)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.lineplot(x=range(2,11), y=arr_silhouette_score_euclidean, color='#000087', linewidth = 4)
sns.scatterplot(x=range(2,11), y=arr_silhouette_score_euclidean, s=300, color='#800000',  linestyle='--')
plt.show()
